":[{"name":"Brewer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a brewer of beer or ale, from Middle English <i>brewere</i> ‘brewer’ (an agent derivative of Old English <i>brēowan</i> ‘to brew’). Compare   Brewster  .","English (of Norman origin): Anglicized form of French <b>Bruyère</b> (see   Bruyere  ), a habitational name from a place so called in Calvados, France, from Old French <i>bruiere</i> ‘heath’.","Americanized form (translation into English) of Dutch   Brouwer  , German   Brauer   or   Breuer  , etc., all occupational names meaning ‘brewer’."],"variants":[{"name":"Brewster","meanings":["English: occupational name for a brewer of beer or ale, from Middle English <i>brewestere</i>, <i>browestere</i> ‘(female) brewer’ (from Old English <i>brēowan</i> ‘to brew’). <i>Brewer</i> is the usual term in southern England, while <i>Brewster</i> is mainly midland, northern, and Scottish.","History: The <i>Mayflower</i> Pilgrim William Brewster (1567–1644) was the son of the bailiff of the manor of Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, home of one of the earliest Puritan congregations. He was a prominent leader in Plymouth Colony from the 1620s until his death."]},{"name":"Brower","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Brewer  .","Altered form of   Brauer   or   Brouwer  ."]}]},{"name":"Katherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Christopher ;  also of   Katherine   and its variants. In the medieval period it was a pet form of   Christian   and   Christiana ."],"variants":[{"name":"Christopher","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Khristophoros</i>, from <i>Khristos</i> ‘Christ’ + <i>pherein</i> ‘to bear’. This was popular among early Christians, conscious of the fact that they were metaphorically bearing Christ in their hearts. A later, over-literal interpretation of the name gave rise to the legend of a saint who actually bore the Christ-child over a stream; he is regarded as the patron of travellers. In England the name was uncommon in the Middle Ages, but became very popular in the 16th century, especially in parts of the North."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":5,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":7,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":40,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":62,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705216,"age":108,"year":"1688","toYear":"1689","julianDay":2337590,"title":"Glorious Revolution","description":"The Glorious Revolution brought the downfall of Catholic King James II and the reign of his Protestant daughter Mary and her Dutch husband, William III of Orange.","url":"http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/civil_war_revolution/glorious_revolution_01.shtml","urlTitle":"BBC - Glorious Revolution","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Katherine Brewer was born in 1580, in North Wraxall, Wiltshire, England. She had at least 2 sons with Richard de Parham."},"et":{"1580–":"1580–Surnud","1560–1626":"1560–1626","1598–1663":"1598–1663","1610–Male":"1610–Surnud","1580–Female":"1580–Surnud","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1610":"1610","1598":"1598","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1663":"1663","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1626":"1626","St Andrew, Holborn, Middlesex, England":"St Andrew, Holborn, Middlesex, England","North Wraxall, Wiltshire, England":"North Wraxall, Wiltshire, England"},"fi":{"1580–":"1580–Kuollut","1560–1626":"1560–1626","1598–1663":"1598–1663","1610–Male":"1610–Kuollut","1580–Female":"1580–Kuollut","1560":"1560","1580":"1580","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1610":"1610","1598":"1598","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1663":"1663","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1626":"1626","St Andrew, Holborn, Middlesex, England":"St Andrew, Holborn, Middlesex, England","North Wraxall, Wiltshire, England":"North Wraxall, Wiltshire, England"},"fr":{"1580–":"1580–Décédée","1560–1626":"1560–1626","1598–1663":"1598–1663","1610–Male":"1610–Décédé","1580–Female":"1580–Décédée","1560":